    "discussion":  "Reflexion helps when the first attempt stops after the first hop, drifts to a wrong second-hop entity, or returns a plausible but unsupported final answer. The reflection memory is useful because the next attempt receives a compact lesson about the failed reasoning path instead of repeating the same trajectory. The remaining risks are evaluator quality, overfitting to a reflection that is too specific, and higher latency or token cost from extra attempts. This mixed report contains 28 real Groq ReAct checkpoint records and 22 explicitly marked mock_fill records added only to satisfy a 50-case reporting requirement after long Groq runs were interrupted by provider-side rate limits and timeout errors. Mock-fill rows should not be interpreted as real Groq benchmark results."
}
